@page "/negative-force"

<PageTitle>Negative Force — Eq (8), (9), (10)</PageTitle>

<h1>Negative Force — Eq (8), (9), (10)</h1>

<blockquote>
    Force can be negative — an individual can actively destroy value. The damage scales with the multiplier: a negative-force individual in a high-M environment does far more harm than in a low-M one. The epistemic gap measures how well the organization can tell the difference.
</blockquote>

<ChartCard Title="Directed Force Waterfall" Description="Eq (8): F_dir = Sum(w_i * f_i). Shows weighted contributions as a waterfall.">
    <ChildContent>
        <WaterfallChart Width="600" Height="400"
                        Items="@_waterfallItems"
                        YLabel="Contribution" />
    </ChildContent>
    <TheoryContent>
        <h4>Equation</h4>
        <KatexBlock Latex="F_{\text{directed}} = \sum_{i} w_i \cdot f_i \qquad \text{where some } f_i < 0 \qquad (8)" />
        <h4>In Plain Language</h4>
        <p>An engineer who is confident, fast, and systematically wrong doesn't just have low force — they have force in the wrong direction. The additive form is needed here because the multiplicative model (Eq 1) can't represent negative contributions. Strong components compensate for weak ones in the additive model, but when some components are actively negative, the sum can go negative too.</p>
        <h4>The Mirror</h4>
        <p>A mirror has no judgment about what it reflects. It reflects brilliant architectural thinking and catastrophic mistakes with equal fluency. It doesn't say "this is a terrible idea." It helps you build the wrong thing faster.</p>
        <h4>Connections</h4>
        <ul>
            <li>Damage scaling Eq (9)</li>
            <li>Epistemic corruption Eq (10)</li>
            <li>Base model Eq (1)</li>
        </ul>
    </TheoryContent>
</ChartCard>

<ChartCard Title="Damage HeatMap" Description="Eq (9): D = M * |F_neg| * tau. Varies M and F_neg to compute damage.">
    <ChildContent>
        <HeatMap Width="600" Height="400"
                 XLabel="Multiplier (M)"
                 YLabel="Negative Force"
                 Data="@_damageData"
                 XValues="@_damageXValues"
                 YValues="@_damageYValues" />
    </ChildContent>
    <TheoryContent>
        <h4>Equation</h4>
        <KatexBlock Latex="D = M \times |F_{\text{negative}}| \times \tau \qquad (9)" />
        <h4>In Plain Language</h4>
        <p>The blast radius of bad judgment scales directly with M. Pre-LLM, a negative-force individual was rate-limited by execution speed. The LLM removes that governor. Equations (4) and (5) don't just widen the gap between good and mediocre output — they widen the gap between good output and actively destructive output.</p>
        <h4>Connections</h4>
        <ul>
            <li>Variance amplifier Eq (4)</li>
            <li>Output gap Eq (5)</li>
            <li>Epistemic corruption Eq (10)</li>
        </ul>
    </TheoryContent>
</ChartCard>

<ChartCard Title="Epistemic Gap HeatMap" Description="Eq (10): Delta = Mp / (Ms * Fi). Varies M_presentation and M_substance.">
    <ChildContent>
        <HeatMap Width="600" Height="400"
                 XLabel="M Presentation"
                 YLabel="M Substance"
                 Data="@_epistemicData"
                 XValues="@_epistemicXValues"
                 YValues="@_epistemicYValues" />
    </ChildContent>
    <TheoryContent>
        <h4>Equation</h4>
        <KatexBlock Latex="\Delta_{\text{epistemic}}(i) = C_{\text{apparent}}(i) - C_{\text{warranted}}(i) \propto \frac{M_p}{M_s(d) \cdot F_i} \qquad (10)" />
        <h4>In Plain Language</h4>
        <p>The epistemic gap is widest when the presentation multiplier (M_p) is high relative to the substance multiplier (M_s) and the user's force (F_i). The output looks brilliant (M_p is always large). The output is brilliant only when M_s·F_i is also large. For a low-force user working on a novel problem (low M_s), the gap between how the output looks and what it's actually worth is enormous.</p>
        <h4>The Mirror</h4>
        <p>Think of Narcissus. He stared at his reflection not because it was accurate but because it was beautiful. The LLM operates identically — when it produces a nuanced response, there appears to be understanding behind the text. But that depth is virtual, a property of the reflection's structure, not evidence of anything behind the surface.</p>
        <h4>Connections</h4>
        <ul>
            <li>Assessment SNR Eq (18)</li>
            <li>Goodhart's trap Eq (19)</li>
            <li>Force dynamics Eq (11)</li>
        </ul>
    </TheoryContent>
</ChartCard>

<FloatingSliderPanel Visible="true" Title="Negative Force Parameters" DefaultY="100">
    <div class="slider-group-header">Eq (8): Directed Force Waterfall</div>
    <ParameterSlider Label="Weight 1" Min="0" Max="1" Step="0.1" Value="@_w1" ValueChanged="OnW1Changed" />
    <ParameterSlider Label="Weight 2" Min="0" Max="1" Step="0.1" Value="@_w2" ValueChanged="OnW2Changed" />
    <ParameterSlider Label="Weight 3" Min="0" Max="1" Step="0.1" Value="@_w3" ValueChanged="OnW3Changed" />
    <ParameterSlider Label="Force 1" Min="-10" Max="10" Step="0.1" Value="@_f1" ValueChanged="OnF1Changed" />
    <ParameterSlider Label="Force 2" Min="-10" Max="10" Step="0.1" Value="@_f2" ValueChanged="OnF2Changed" />
    <ParameterSlider Label="Force 3" Min="-10" Max="10" Step="0.1" Value="@_f3" ValueChanged="OnF3Changed" />
    <div class="slider-group-header">Eq (9): Damage HeatMap</div>
    <ParameterSlider Label="M" Min="0.5" Max="5" Step="0.1" Value="@_m" ValueChanged="OnMChanged" />
    <ParameterSlider Label="F_neg" Min="0" Max="10" Step="0.1" Value="@_forceNeg" ValueChanged="OnForceNegChanged" />
    <ParameterSlider Label="Tau" Min="0.1" Max="5" Step="0.1" Value="@_tau" ValueChanged="OnTauChanged" />
    <div class="slider-group-header">Eq (10): Epistemic Gap</div>
    <ParameterSlider Label="M Presentation" Min="0.5" Max="5" Step="0.1" Value="@_mPresentation" ValueChanged="OnMPresentationChanged" />
    <ParameterSlider Label="M Substance" Min="0.5" Max="5" Step="0.1" Value="@_mSubstance" ValueChanged="OnMSubstanceChanged" />
    <ParameterSlider Label="Force Individual" Min="0.1" Max="10" Step="0.1" Value="@_forceIndividual" ValueChanged="OnForceIndividualChanged" />
</FloatingSliderPanel>

@code {
    // Waterfall sliders
    private double _w1 = 0.3, _w2 = 0.5, _w3 = 0.2;
    private double _f1 = 5, _f2 = -3, _f3 = 7;

    // Damage sliders
    private double _m = 2;
    private double _forceNeg = 3;
    private double _tau = 1;

    // Epistemic gap sliders
    private double _mPresentation = 3;
    private double _mSubstance = 1;
    private double _forceIndividual = 5;

    // Waterfall data
    private List<WaterfallItem> _waterfallItems = new();

    // Damage heatmap data
    private double[,] _damageData = new double[0, 0];
    private double[] _damageXValues = Array.Empty<double>();
    private double[] _damageYValues = Array.Empty<double>();

    // Epistemic heatmap data
    private double[,] _epistemicData = new double[0, 0];
    private double[] _epistemicXValues = Array.Empty<double>();
    private double[] _epistemicYValues = Array.Empty<double>();

    protected override void OnInitialized() => Recalculate();

    private void OnW1Changed(double v) { _w1 = v; Recalculate(); }
    private void OnW2Changed(double v) { _w2 = v; Recalculate(); }
    private void OnW3Changed(double v) { _w3 = v; Recalculate(); }
    private void OnF1Changed(double v) { _f1 = v; Recalculate(); }
    private void OnF2Changed(double v) { _f2 = v; Recalculate(); }
    private void OnF3Changed(double v) { _f3 = v; Recalculate(); }
    private void OnMChanged(double v) { _m = v; Recalculate(); }
    private void OnForceNegChanged(double v) { _forceNeg = v; Recalculate(); }
    private void OnTauChanged(double v) { _tau = v; Recalculate(); }
    private void OnMPresentationChanged(double v) { _mPresentation = v; Recalculate(); }
    private void OnMSubstanceChanged(double v) { _mSubstance = v; Recalculate(); }
    private void OnForceIndividualChanged(double v) { _forceIndividual = v; Recalculate(); }

    private void Recalculate()
    {
        ComputeWaterfall();
        ComputeDamageHeatMap();
        ComputeEpistemicHeatMap();
    }

    private void ComputeWaterfall()
    {
        var weights = new[] { _w1, _w2, _w3 };
        var forces = new[] { _f1, _f2, _f3 };

        _waterfallItems = new List<WaterfallItem>
        {
            new($"w1*f1 ({_w1:F1}*{_f1:F1})", _w1 * _f1),
            new($"w2*f2 ({_w2:F1}*{_f2:F1})", _w2 * _f2),
            new($"w3*f3 ({_w3:F1}*{_f3:F1})", _w3 * _f3),
            new("Total", NegativeForce.DirectedForce(weights, forces), IsTotal: true)
        };
    }

    private void ComputeDamageHeatMap()
    {
        const int steps = 20;
        _damageXValues = new double[steps];
        _damageYValues = new double[steps];
        _damageData = new double[steps, steps];

        for (int i = 0; i < steps; i++)
            _damageXValues[i] = 0.5 + i * 4.5 / (steps - 1);
        for (int j = 0; j < steps; j++)
            _damageYValues[j] = j * 10.0 / (steps - 1);

        for (int r = 0; r < steps; r++)
        {
            for (int c = 0; c < steps; c++)
            {
                _damageData[r, c] = NegativeForce.Damage(_damageXValues[c], _damageYValues[r], _tau);
            }
        }
    }

    private void ComputeEpistemicHeatMap()
    {
        const int steps = 20;
        _epistemicXValues = new double[steps];
        _epistemicYValues = new double[steps];
        _epistemicData = new double[steps, steps];

        for (int i = 0; i < steps; i++)
            _epistemicXValues[i] = 0.5 + i * 4.5 / (steps - 1);
        for (int j = 0; j < steps; j++)
            _epistemicYValues[j] = 0.5 + j * 4.5 / (steps - 1);

        for (int r = 0; r < steps; r++)
        {
            for (int c = 0; c < steps; c++)
            {
                _epistemicData[r, c] = NegativeForce.EpistemicGap(_epistemicXValues[c], _epistemicYValues[r], _forceIndividual);
            }
        }
    }
}
